<li id="cite_note-58"><b><a href="#cite_ref-58" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.bookrags.com/news/afghanistan-moc/" class="external text" title="http://www.bookrags.com/news/afghanistan-moc/" rel="nofollow">Afghanistan</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-Weil-TheNaturalMind-17-59">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Weil-TheNaturalMind-17_59-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Weil-TheNaturalMind-17_59-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFWeil1985"><a href="/wiki/Andrew_Weil" title="Andrew Weil">Weil, Andrew</a> (1985). <i>The Natural Mind—An Investigation of Drugs and the Higher Consciousness</i>. Houghton Mifflin. pp.&#160;17–18. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0395911567" class="internal">ISBN 0-395-91156-7</a>.  "The use of drugs to alter consciousness is nothing new. It has been a feature of human life in all places on the earth and all ages of history. In fact, to my knowledge, the only people lacking a traditional intoxicant are the Eskimos, who had the misfortune to be unable to grow anything and had to wait for the white men to bring them alcohol. Alcohol of course, has always been the most commonly used drug simply because it does not take much effort to discover that the consumption of fermented juices produces interesting variations from ordinary consciousness.<br />
&#160;&#160;The ubiquity of drug use is so striking that it must represent a basic human appetite. Yet many Americans seem to feel that the contemporary drug scene is something new, something qualitatively different from what has gone before. This attitude is peculiar because all that is really happening is a change in drug preference. There is no evidence that a greater percentage of Americans are taking drugs, only that younger Americans are coming to prefer illegal drugs like marijuana and hallucinogens to alcohol. Therefore, people who insist that everyone is suddenly taking drugs must not see alcohol in the category of drugs. Evidence that this is precisely the case is abundant, and it proves another example of how emotional biases lead us to formulate unhelpful conceptions. Drug taking is bad. We drink alcohol. Therefore alcohol is not a drug. It is, instead, a ‘pick-me-up,’ a ‘thirst quencher,’ a ‘social lubricant,’ ‘an indispensable accompaniment to fine food,’ and a variety of other euphemisms. Or, if it is a drug, at least it is not one of those bad drugs that the hippies use."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Natural+Mind%E2%80%94An+Investigation+of+Drugs+and+the+Higher+Consciousness&amp;rft.aulast=Weil&amp;rft.aufirst=Andrew&amp;rft.au=Weil%2C+Andrew&amp;rft.date=1985&amp;rft.pages=pp.%26nbsp%3B17%E2%80%9318&amp;rft.pub=Houghton+Mifflin&amp;rft.isbn=0-395-91156-7&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Arguments_for_and_against_drug_prohibition"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Shulgin-Pihkal-60"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Shulgin-Pihkal_60-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFShulginAnn_Shulgin1991"><a href="/wiki/Alexander_Shulgin" title="Alexander Shulgin">Shulgin, Alexander</a>; Ann Shulgin (1991). <i>PiHKAL: A Chemical Love Story</i>. Transform Press. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0963009605" class="internal">ISBN 0-9630096-0-5</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=PiHKAL%3A+A+Chemical+Love+Story&amp;rft.aulast=Shulgin&amp;rft.aufirst=Alexander&amp;rft.au=Shulgin%2C+Alexander&amp;rft.au=Ann+Shulgin&amp;rft.date=1991&amp;rft.pub=Transform+Press&amp;rft.isbn=0-9630096-0-5&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Arguments_for_and_against_drug_prohibition"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Weil-TheNaturalMind-19-61"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Weil-TheNaturalMind-19_61-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFWeil1985"><a href="/wiki/Andrew_Weil" title="Andrew Weil">Weil, Andrew</a> (1985). <i>The Natural Mind—An Investigation of Drugs and the Higher Consciousness</i>. Houghton Mifflin. pp.&#160;19–20. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0395911567" class="internal">ISBN 0-395-91156-7</a>.  "It is my belief that the desire to alter consciousness periodically is an innate, normal drive analogous to hunger or the sexual drive. Note that I do not say ‘desire to alter consciousness by means of chemical agents.’ Drugs a merely one means of satisfying this drive; there are many others, and I will discuss them in due course. In postulating an inborn drive of this sort, I am not advancing a proposition to be proved or disproved but simply a model to be tried out for usefulness in simplifying our understanding of our observations. The model I propose is consistent with observable evidence. In particular, the omnipresence of the phenomenon argues that we are dealing not with something socially or culturally based but rather with a biological characteristic of the species. Furthermore, the need for periods of nonordinary consciousness begins to be expressed at ages far too young for it to have much to do with social conditioning. Anyone who watches very young children without revealing his presence will find them regularly practicing techniques that induce striking changes in mental states. Three- and four-year-olds, for example, commonly whirl themselves into vertiginous stupors. They hyperventilate and have other children squeeze them around the chest until they faint. They also choke each other to produce loss of consciousness.<br />
&#160;&#160;To my knowledge these practices appear spontaneously among children of all societies, and I suspect they have done so throughout history as well. In our society, children quickly learn to keep this sort of play out of sight of grownups, who instinctively try to stop them. The sight of a child being throttled into unconsciousness scares the parent, but the child seems to have a wonderful time; at least, he goes right off and does it again."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Natural+Mind%E2%80%94An+Investigation+of+Drugs+and+the+Higher+Consciousness&amp;rft.aulast=Weil&amp;rft.aufirst=Andrew&amp;rft.au=Weil%2C+Andrew&amp;rft.date=1985&amp;rft.pages=pp.%26nbsp%3B19%E2%80%9320&amp;rft.pub=Houghton+Mifflin&amp;rft.isbn=0-395-91156-7&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Arguments_for_and_against_drug_prohibition"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-McKenna-FoodOfTheGods-62"><b><a href="#cite_ref-McKenna-FoodOfTheGods_62-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFMcKenna1993"><a href="/wiki/Terence_McKenna" title="Terence McKenna">McKenna, Terence</a> (1993). <i>Food of the Gods: The Search for the Original Tree of Knowledge—A Radical History of Plants, Drugs, and Human Evolution</i>. Bantam. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0553371304" class="internal">ISBN 0-553-37130-4</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Food+of+the+Gods%3A+The+Search+for+the+Original+Tree+of+Knowledge%E2%80%94A+Radical+History+of+Plants%2C+Drugs%2C+and+Human+Evolution&amp;rft.aulast=McKenna&amp;rft.aufirst=Terence&amp;rft.au=McKenna%2C+Terence&amp;rft.date=1993&amp;rft.pub=Bantam&amp;rft.isbn=0-553-37130-4&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Arguments_for_and_against_drug_prohibition"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Lilly-TheCentreOfTheCyclone-63"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Lilly-TheCentreOfTheCyclone_63-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFLilly2006"><a href="/wiki/John_C._Lilly" title="John C. Lilly">Lilly, John C.</a> (2006). <i>The Centre of the Cyclone</i>. Marion Boyars Publishers Ltd.. p.&#160;6. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/1842300040" class="internal">ISBN 1-84230-004-0</a>.  "It is my firm belief that the experience of higher states of consciousness is necessary for survival of the human species"</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Centre+of+the+Cyclone&amp;rft.aulast=Lilly&amp;rft.aufirst=John+C.&amp;rft.au=Lilly%2C+John+C.&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.pages=p.%26nbsp%3B6&amp;rft.pub=Marion+Boyars+Publishers+Ltd.&amp;rft.isbn=1-84230-004-0&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Arguments_for_and_against_drug_prohibition"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Huxley-TheDoorsOfPerception-64"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Huxley-TheDoorsOfPerception_64-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFHuxley2004"><a href="/wiki/Aldous_Huxley" title="Aldous Huxley">Huxley, Aldous</a> (2004). <i>The Doors of Perception and Heaven and Hell</i>. Harper Perennial Modern Classics. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0060595183" class="internal">ISBN 0-06059-518-3</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Doors+of+Perception+and+Heaven+and+Hell&amp;rft.aulast=Huxley&amp;rft.aufirst=Aldous&amp;rft.au=Huxley%2C+Aldous&amp;rft.date=2004&amp;rft.pub=Harper+Perennial+Modern+Classics&amp;rft.isbn=0-06059-518-3&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Arguments_for_and_against_drug_prohibition"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-65"><b><a href="#cite_ref-65" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFCommon_Sense_for_Drug_Policy2007">Common Sense for Drug Policy (2007-05-29). <a href="http://www.drugwarfacts.org/thenethe.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.drugwarfacts.org/thenethe.htm" rel="nofollow">"The Netherlands and the United States: A Comparison"</a>. <i>Drug War Facts</i><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.drugwarfacts.org/thenethe.htm" class="external free" title="http://www.drugwarfacts.org/thenethe.htm" rel="nofollow">http://www.drugwarfacts.org/thenethe.htm</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2008-03-07</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=The+Netherlands+and+the+United+States%3A+A+Comparison&amp;rft.atitle=Drug+War+Facts&amp;rft.aulast=Common+Sense+for+Drug+Policy&amp;rft.au=Common+Sense+for+Drug+Policy&amp;rft.date=2007-05-29&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.drugwarfacts.org%2Fthenethe.htm&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Arguments_for_and_against_drug_prohibition"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-66"><b><a href="#cite_ref-66" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://www.cdc.gov/ncipc/factsheets/drving.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.cdc.gov/ncipc/factsheets/drving.htm" rel="nofollow">"Impaired Driving"</a>. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.cdc.gov/ncipc/factsheets/drving.htm" class="external free" title="http://www.cdc.gov/ncipc/factsheets/drving.htm" rel="nofollow">http://www.cdc.gov/ncipc/factsheets/drving.htm</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2008-05-11</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Impaired+Driving&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.pub=Centers+for+Disease+Control+and+Prevention&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cdc.gov%2Fncipc%2Ffactsheets%2Fdrving.htm&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Arguments_for_and_against_drug_prohibition"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-67"><b><a href="#cite_ref-67" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="" id="CITEREFNuttKingSaulsburyBlakemore2007">Nutt, David; King, Leslie; Saulsbury, William; Blakemore, Colin (March 2007), "<a href="http://www.antiproibizionisti.it/public/docs/thelancet_20070323.pdf" class="external text" title="http://www.antiproibizionisti.it/public/docs/thelancet_20070323.pdf" rel="nofollow">Development of a rational scale to assess the harm of drugs of potential misuse</a>", <i>The Lancet</i> <b>369</b> (9566): 1047–1053, <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<span class="neverexpand"><a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1016%2FS0140-6736%2807%2960464-4" class="external text" title="http://dx.doi.org/10.1016%2FS0140-6736%2807%2960464-4" rel="nofollow">10.1016/S0140-6736(07)60464-4</a></span><span class="printonly">, <a href="http://www.antiproibizionisti.it/public/docs/thelancet_20070323.pdf" class="external free" title="http://www.antiproibizionisti.it/public/docs/thelancet_20070323.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://www.antiproibizionisti.it/public/docs/thelancet_20070323.pdf</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">, retrieved on 2007-03-23</span></cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.atitle=Development+of+a+rational+scale+to+assess+the+harm+of+drugs+of+potential+misuse&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Lancet&amp;rft.aulast=Nutt&amp;rft.aufirst=David&amp;rft.au=Nutt%2C+David&amp;rft.au=King%2C+Leslie&amp;rft.au=Saulsbury%2C+William&amp;rft.au=Blakemore%2C+Colin&amp;rft.date=March+2007&amp;rft.volume=369&amp;rft.issue=9566&amp;rft.pages=1047%E2%80%931053&amp;rft_id=info:doi/10.1016%2FS0140-6736%2807%2960464-4&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.antiproibizionisti.it%2Fpublic%2Fdocs%2Fthelancet_20070323.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Arguments_for_and_against_drug_prohibition"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-68"><b><a href="#cite_ref-68" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.drugwatch.org/CEDARS/MarDeaths2002e.pdf" class="external text" title="http://www.drugwatch.org/CEDARS/MarDeaths2002e.pdf" rel="nofollow">Marijuana-Only Drug Abuse Deaths—2002</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-69"><b><a href="#cite_ref-69" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFCommon_Sense_for_Drug_Policy2007">Common Sense for Drug Policy (2007-05-16). <a href="http://www.drugwarfacts.org/causes.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.drugwarfacts.org/causes.htm" rel="nofollow">"Annual Causes of Death in the United States"</a>. <i>Drug War Facts</i><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.drugwarfacts.org/causes.htm" class="external free" title="http://www.drugwarfacts.org/causes.htm" rel="nofollow">http://www.drugwarfacts.org/causes.htm</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2008-03-07</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Annual+Causes+of+Death+in+the+United+States&amp;rft.atitle=Drug+War+Facts&amp;rft.aulast=Common+Sense+for+Drug+Policy&amp;rft.au=Common+Sense+for+Drug+Policy&amp;rft.date=2007-05-16&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.drugwarfacts.org%2Fcauses.htm&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Arguments_for_and_against_drug_prohibition"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-70"><b><a href="#cite_ref-70" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFTrimnell2007">Trimnell, Edward (2007-02-03). <a href="http://www.edwardtrimnell.com/us_drug_laws.htm" class="external text" title="http://www.edwardtrimnell.com/us_drug_laws.htm" rel="nofollow">"The inconsistent nature of U.S. drug laws"</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.edwardtrimnell.com/us_drug_laws.htm" class="external free" title="http://www.edwardtrimnell.com/us_drug_laws.htm" rel="nofollow">http://www.edwardtrimnell.com/us_drug_laws.htm</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2008-05-11</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=The+inconsistent+nature+of+U.S.+drug+laws&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.aulast=Trimnell&amp;rft.aufirst=Edward&amp;rft.au=Trimnell%2C+Edward&amp;rft.date=2007-02-03&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.edwardtrimnell.com%2Fus_drug_laws.htm&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Arguments_for_and_against_drug_prohibition"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-71"><b><a href="#cite_ref-71" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://www.lindesmith.org/library/factsheets/effectivenes/index.cfm" class="external text" title="http://www.lindesmith.org/library/factsheets/effectivenes/index.cfm" rel="nofollow">Effectiveness of the War on Drugs</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-72"><b><a href="#cite_ref-72" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREF.5B.5BHuman_Rights_Watch.5D.5D2000"><a href="/wiki/Human_Rights_Watch" title="Human Rights Watch">Human Rights Watch</a> (2000-05-01). <a href="http://www.hrw.org/reports/2000/usa/" class="external text" title="http://www.hrw.org/reports/2000/usa/" rel="nofollow">"Punishment and Prejudice: Racial Disparities in the War on Drugs"</a>. <i>Report</i><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.hrw.org/reports/2000/usa/" class="external free" title="http://www.hrw.org/reports/2000/usa/" rel="nofollow">http://www.hrw.org/reports/2000/usa/</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2008-03-09</span>.  "Ostensibly color blind, the war on drugs has been waged disproportionately against black Americans."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Punishment+and+Prejudice%3A+Racial+Disparities+in+the+War+on+Drugs&amp;rft.atitle=Report&amp;rft.aulast=%5B%5BHuman+Rights+Watch%5D%5D&amp;rft.au=%5B%5BHuman+Rights+Watch%5D%5D&amp;rft.date=2000-05-01&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.hrw.org%2Freports%2F2000%2Fusa%2F&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Arguments_for_and_against_drug_prohibition"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-73"><b><a href="#cite_ref-73" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web" id="CITEREFCoyle2002">Coyle, Michael (2002-11-22). <a href="http://www.sentencingproject.org/Admin/Documents/publications/rd_raceandclass_penalties.pdf" class="external text" title="http://www.sentencingproject.org/Admin/Documents/publications/rd_raceandclass_penalties.pdf" rel="nofollow">"Race and class penalties in crack cocaine sentencing"</a> (PDF). <a href="/wiki/Sentencing_Project" title="Sentencing Project">Sentencing Project</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://www.sentencingproject.org/Admin/Documents/publications/rd_raceandclass_penalties.pdf" class="external free" title="http://www.sentencingproject.org/Admin/Documents/publications/rd_raceandclass_penalties.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://www.sentencingproject.org/Admin/Documents/publications/rd_raceandclass_penalties.pdf</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2008-03-09</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Race+and+class+penalties+in+crack+cocaine+sentencing&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.aulast=Coyle&amp;rft.aufirst=Michael&amp;rft.au=Coyle%2C+Michael&amp;rft.date=2002-11-22&amp;rft.pub=%5B%5BSentencing+Project%5D%5D&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.sentencingproject.org%2FAdmin%2FDocuments%2Fpublications%2Frd_raceandclass_penalties.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Arguments_for_and_against_drug_prohibition"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-74"><b><a href="#cite_ref-74" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFGlasscoteSussex.2C_J.N..2C_Jaffe.2C_J.H..2C_Ball.2C_J..2C_Brill.2C_L.1972">Glasscote, Raymond M.; Sussex, J.N., Jaffe, J.H., Ball, J., Brill, L. (1972). <i>The Treatment of Drug Abuse: Programs, Problems, Prospects</i>. Washington, D.C.: Joint Information Service of the <a href="/wiki/American_Psychiatric_Association" title="American Psychiatric Association">American Psychiatric Association</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Mind_(charity)" title="Mind (charity)">National Association for Mental Health</a>.  "… as a general rule, we reserve the term drug abuse to apply to the illegal, nonmedical use of a limited number of substances, most of them drugs, which have properties of altering the mental state in ways that are considered by social norms and defined by statute to be inappropriate, undesirable, harmful, threatening, or, at minimum, culture-alien."</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Treatment+of+Drug+Abuse%3A+Programs%2C+Problems%2C+Prospects&amp;rft.aulast=Glasscote&amp;rft.aufirst=Raymond+M.&amp;rft.au=Glasscote%2C+Raymond+M.&amp;rft.au=Sussex%2C+J.N.%2C+Jaffe%2C+J.H.%2C+Ball%2C+J.%2C+Brill%2C+L.&amp;rft.date=1972&amp;rft.place=Washington%2C+D.C.&amp;rft.pub=Joint+Information+Service+of+the+%5B%5BAmerican+Psychiatric+Association%5D%5D+and+the+%5B%5BMind+%28charity%29%7CNational+Association+for+Mental+Health%5D%5D&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Arguments_for_and_against_drug_prohibition"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
</ol>
